    "text": "The challenge of translating long-term memory into embodied plans specifically arises when an agent maintains an explicit world model that can be overwritten, not from partial observability alone.",
    "topic": "conditions for translation challenge"
  },
  {
    "text": "Partial observability without overwritable world states does not create the translation problem; many partially observable agents act directly from beliefs without converting memory into plans.",
    "topic": "scope of partial observability"
  },
  {
    "text": "Approaches that translate memory into plans are methods that jointly handle partial observability and overwriting, making the translation challenge a subproblem of that combined difficulty.",
    "topic": "classification of translation"
  },
  {
    "text": "The WorldLines paper defines the translation as a subproblem of partial observability and overwritten world states, not as a fundamental challenge independent of either condition.",
    "topic": "WorldLines classification"
  }
]
